Despite being called "Central schemes", Tamil Nadu ends up bearing a higher share of the cost. 

For example, in PMAY (Rural), the Centre is supposed to contribute 60%, but actually provides only 39% - the State covers 61%.

In NSAP pension schemes too, though they are claimed as 100% funded by the Union, Tamil Nadu gives ₹1,200–₹1,500 to beneficiaries, while the Centre gives just ₹300–₹500.

This is not true cooperative federalism, it's cost shifting in the name of central schemes.

